06:31.160 --> 06:36.600
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:39.420 --> 06:41.120
And here are your hosts.

06:45.660 --> 06:48.020
This is Bill Vernon and David Carson.

06:48.300 --> 06:51.700
Science fiction writer Edward Bryant is the subject of today's show.

06:51.700 --> 06:57.440
Probably Bryant's most important contribution to date is his collection of connected stories called Cinnabar.

06:57.640 --> 07:02.300
Here Bryant tells something about the city of Cinnabar, the place around which the stories revolve.

07:03.080 --> 07:12.440
No matter whether it's a short story or a novel, and no matter how complex the ultimate product might be originally,

07:12.440 --> 07:17.660
there always is the single image somewhere along the line that everything else generated from.

07:17.660 --> 07:23.380
In the case of Cinnabar, I suppose the overriding image is the city itself.

07:23.840 --> 07:31.740
The city that exists presumably millions of years in our future and may or may not exist here on Earth.

07:31.740 --> 07:36.400
That's never really spelled out, nor did I feel it important to do so.

07:36.500 --> 07:43.020
Although I suspect to pin down, I would suggest that Cinnabar is probably very close to Phoenix, Arizona.

07:44.120 --> 07:45.680
I shouldn't be surprised.

07:47.180 --> 07:57.300
But in the late 1960s, I just had the image of the far future, very colorful, emerald city of Oz,

07:57.640 --> 08:01.720
sort of apparition, wavering out there on the desert horizon.

08:01.720 --> 08:11.120
And of course, once the image was there, then all the questions of both fiction in general and science fiction in particular generated,

08:11.380 --> 08:15.000
such as, okay, what is that city all about?

08:15.140 --> 08:15.980
Who lives there?

08:16.100 --> 08:16.920
What do they do?

08:16.920 --> 08:26.260
I wanted to write about a city of such sophistication and decadence that science and technology,

08:26.600 --> 08:32.140
as Arthur C. Clarke put in a different context, might as well be magic.

08:33.420 --> 08:41.720
And I wanted to, in terms of the human element, investigate what would people do with their access to immortality,

08:41.860 --> 08:45.260
with their access to technological powers beyond compare.

08:46.140 --> 08:51.480
Would their lives be any less screwed up than they are now in 20th century America, or not?

08:51.700 --> 08:56.700
So again, I was going back to that original premise that I believe in,

08:56.860 --> 09:01.080
that good fiction is about people and their relationships.

09:02.060 --> 09:05.980
And if you have access to physical immortality, for example,

09:06.140 --> 09:10.500
how does this affect your relationship with the people that are closest to you

09:10.500 --> 09:13.300
and the people that you interact with every day on the street?

09:14.120 --> 09:18.220
And that's what Cinnabar finally is all about.

09:19.080 --> 09:22.260
Although Bryant conceived of the stories as separate entities,

09:22.580 --> 09:25.520
he eventually realized how closely tied they all are.

09:26.280 --> 09:30.460
And it came as a great surprise to me, as I wrote these stories,

09:31.240 --> 09:34.240
about that fabulous city,

09:34.520 --> 09:41.280
that there was an all-over structure that seemed to be coming out independent of each individual story.

09:41.540 --> 09:46.460
And that's why when you read the stories all together in a book,

09:46.620 --> 09:50.720
I feel there is a clear-cut beginning and a clear-cut ending,

09:50.720 --> 09:55.640
and there is progress made through the stories,

09:55.640 --> 10:00.380
almost as though one were reading a from-scratch novel,

10:00.640 --> 10:02.260
even though, of course, it isn't.

10:02.540 --> 10:06.760
I weasel a lot with the definition of what is a novel there and what isn't.

10:07.840 --> 10:10.980
Still, the background is the same from story to story.

10:11.100 --> 10:14.020
Most of the characters are the same from story to story.

10:14.980 --> 10:18.040
The origin of the name Cinnabar is an interesting story.

10:18.480 --> 10:20.040
Here Bryant tells us what inspired it.

10:20.960 --> 10:22.220
Now the city title,

10:25.140 --> 10:29.980
strangely enough, came originally from a photograph of a horse.

10:31.580 --> 10:39.460
My mother, in her living room, has a beautiful photograph of the head of a palomino.

10:40.860 --> 10:44.500
This was a picture she told me about when I was growing up,

10:44.520 --> 10:47.600
because this was the horse that she used to ride in the summers

10:47.600 --> 10:51.140
out at a dude ranch in upstate New York called the Cinnabar.

10:52.320 --> 10:55.360
And I'd always loved the sound of the word.

10:55.800 --> 10:58.900
It conjured up all sorts of images for me

10:58.900 --> 11:03.160
that I think went far beyond your standard upstate New York dude ranch.

11:03.960 --> 11:07.120
More on Edward Bryant's Cinnabar next time.

