12:43.680 --> 12:47.380
Our show today centers again on the Cinnabar stories by Edward Bryant.

12:47.700 --> 12:51.980
In the acknowledgments of Cinnabar, Bryant writes to Joan Bernat,

12:52.120 --> 12:54.480
who pioneered in the writing of Cinnabar stories.

12:54.820 --> 12:56.780
Here he explains this acknowledgment.

12:57.360 --> 13:02.900
Joan Bernat was a very good writer who did a number of stories at the early Clarion workshops,

13:02.920 --> 13:05.560
which were published in various anthologies,

13:05.560 --> 13:07.280
and I have no idea where she is now.

13:08.240 --> 13:11.840
But at one point in the workshop, we'd done an exercise

13:11.840 --> 13:15.380
in which each of us came up with various narrative hooks,

13:15.640 --> 13:20.620
first lines of stories which were calculated to catch the interest of the reader.

13:21.500 --> 13:26.780
And I had done a story hook which went along the lines of,

13:27.580 --> 13:32.920
oh, I think the road to Cinnabar was lined with the shells of burnt-out school buses.

13:34.220 --> 13:38.500
And I had no particular reason for coming up with this line other than,

13:38.780 --> 13:40.940
to me, it was interesting.

13:41.220 --> 13:45.500
And also this was vaguely tied in with my image of Cinnabar the city.

13:45.980 --> 13:50.700
Well, a number of people in the workshop borrowed other people's narrative hooks

13:50.700 --> 13:51.920
and wrote stories around them.

13:52.000 --> 13:54.820
And Joan Bernat actually did the first Cinnabar story

13:54.820 --> 13:59.380
in the sense that she wrote a story which started with that line.

14:01.020 --> 14:03.820
And her Cinnabar was not quite the same as mine,

14:03.820 --> 14:06.880
but still there was something of the feeling about it,

14:07.120 --> 14:11.720
the almost surrealistic image of the city wavering on the horizon,

14:11.720 --> 14:15.580
the city which is totally cut off from the entire rest of the world.

14:15.580 --> 14:19.360
In fact, for all intents and purposes, is the entire world.

14:19.980 --> 14:24.300
And so that's why Joan Bernat got the acknowledgement at the beginning of the book.

14:24.800 --> 14:28.820
The stories collected in Cinnabar are not the only Cinnabar stories.

14:29.140 --> 14:30.680
Others have been published elsewhere.

14:31.060 --> 14:35.200
We asked Brian if he has plans to write still other stories in the Cinnabar milieu.

14:35.960 --> 14:37.320
I've thought about it.

14:37.580 --> 14:41.940
I have notes on several Cinnabar stories,

14:42.000 --> 14:45.500
including the possibility of doing five novelettes,

14:45.560 --> 14:52.160
which would come together as another makeup novel about the character Jade Blue.

14:52.520 --> 14:58.960
My publisher and I would like to do a new edition of Cinnabar

14:58.960 --> 15:00.880
with a brand new Cinnabar story in it.

15:01.360 --> 15:02.720
But I don't know.

15:02.720 --> 15:06.000
I just haven't been able to do a Cinnabar story.

15:06.120 --> 15:13.100
It may be that its time has passed in terms of my own professional nature.

15:14.760 --> 15:18.020
The Cinnabar stories that I've got planned out would take place

15:18.020 --> 15:20.380
before the time of the stories in the book itself

15:20.380 --> 15:22.600
because, of course, at the end of the book,

15:22.780 --> 15:25.580
I don't think I'm giving away any plot secrets here.

15:26.160 --> 15:28.180
Cinnabar is in the process of being destroyed.

15:28.180 --> 15:35.380
I've had no desire to write stories about Cinnabar after the fall.

15:35.800 --> 15:38.040
But before, there are still possibilities.

15:38.400 --> 15:39.900
I would like to do, for example,

15:41.080 --> 15:43.920
a story about a man in Cinnabar

15:43.920 --> 15:48.800
who comes up with the greatest decadent luxury anyone could have.

15:48.800 --> 15:54.340
I thought for a long time about what single luxury would be the most decadent,

15:54.520 --> 15:58.920
the most useless example of conspicuous affluence.

15:59.260 --> 16:03.960
And I realized, of course, that probably what would be comprised in that

16:03.960 --> 16:05.900
would be having your own roller coaster.

16:06.720 --> 16:10.820
I mean, think how decadent to have your own roller coaster sitting out behind your house,

16:10.860 --> 16:14.240
which only you use, or your friends, of course.

16:14.240 --> 16:17.820
And so I immediately, because I love roller coasters a lot,

16:17.980 --> 16:21.000
started to design my own version of the ultimate roller coaster.

16:21.720 --> 16:28.820
And that is going to be the central image in that particular story, if it's ever written.

16:29.260 --> 16:32.000
Another Cinnabar story, which is yet unwritten,

16:32.260 --> 16:38.280
is what happens when Tourmaline Hayes decides to have an enormous party

16:38.280 --> 16:42.720
at which she invites every single one of her old lovers,

16:42.960 --> 16:44.960
of which she has quite a few.

16:45.800 --> 16:50.440
And this will simply be a party at which you have no idea

16:50.440 --> 16:54.100
whether it's going to be a romantic comedy or a murder mystery.

16:54.360 --> 16:56.120
A lot of possibilities there.

16:56.860 --> 16:59.580
In our next show, we'll talk more about Edward Bryant.

