This is David Carson.

18:32.780 --> 18:33.480
And Bill Vernon.

18:33.820 --> 18:37.300
Today we continue with our interview with science fiction author Edward Bryant.

18:37.680 --> 18:40.200
Those who are at all familiar with Bryant's work

18:40.200 --> 18:43.160
have certainly come across his apparent fascination with sharks.

18:43.160 --> 18:46.200
Here he explains how this attraction was spawned,

18:46.220 --> 18:49.160
then how it led to the famous short story titled simply,

18:49.620 --> 18:49.800
Shark.

18:50.800 --> 18:51.920
Why sharks?

18:53.840 --> 18:55.660
You know, when people visit my apartment,

18:55.660 --> 18:57.280
they see all sorts of shark paraphernalia,

18:58.000 --> 19:00.160
you know, jaws mounted on backboards

19:00.160 --> 19:03.900
and shark mobiles, shark paintings,

19:04.080 --> 19:05.020
and so forth and so on.

19:06.020 --> 19:08.700
The reason for the shark motif,

19:09.560 --> 19:14.200
and the reason that I suppose I've adopted the shark as a sort of totem,

19:14.560 --> 19:17.000
is because in the early 70s,

19:17.630 --> 19:21.500
one of my closest friends had dreamed the night before,

19:21.720 --> 19:23.300
and she told me about this at breakfast,

19:23.300 --> 19:26.360
that she had been in the body of a shark.

19:26.680 --> 19:31.100
She had seen the world through shark-colored lenses.

19:33.280 --> 19:35.560
And we talked about this for a while,

19:35.740 --> 19:38.780
you know, got past the obvious Freudian symbolism of it all,

19:39.980 --> 19:41.900
and I was fascinated by the dream.

19:43.380 --> 19:45.800
Then she catalyzed action by saying,

19:45.920 --> 19:49.680
listen, why don't you write a story about sharks?

19:49.960 --> 19:51.700
Now, I didn't know anything about sharks.

19:51.700 --> 19:54.840
I was just an inland boy who'd grown up far from the sea,

19:54.860 --> 19:57.500
and although the ocean has always fascinated me,

19:57.600 --> 19:58.580
I didn't know about sharks.

19:58.760 --> 20:00.140
But I did my research,

20:00.380 --> 20:02.000
just as with, say, particle theory.

20:02.000 --> 20:03.680
I found out about sharks.

20:03.800 --> 20:06.340
I became intrigued by their position

20:06.340 --> 20:08.640
in the evolutionary scheme of things,

20:08.720 --> 20:11.120
how incredibly well-developed they are.

20:11.380 --> 20:14.640
And I was also struck by such images

20:14.640 --> 20:16.800
as the fact that the shark

20:16.800 --> 20:19.860
is the major species of creature

20:19.860 --> 20:22.500
which is hostile to human beings,

20:22.500 --> 20:25.000
which is in no danger of extinction,

20:25.480 --> 20:26.480
at least at this point.

20:27.300 --> 20:31.740
So I took my friend's original dream

20:31.740 --> 20:33.780
and I said, okay,

20:34.280 --> 20:37.300
I've got a character who wants to be a shark.

20:37.620 --> 20:39.660
Why does she want to be a shark?

20:39.880 --> 20:41.540
How does she become a shark,

20:41.760 --> 20:44.000
both metaphorically and literally?

20:44.360 --> 20:47.800
And that's how the original shark story generated.

20:48.980 --> 20:51.340
I realized after finishing the story

20:51.340 --> 20:54.280
that there were other things that involved sharks

20:54.280 --> 20:56.420
that I had not dealt with in the story

20:56.420 --> 21:00.420
that I would treat in various other pieces.

21:08.620 --> 21:10.100
When Bryant's friends got wind

21:10.100 --> 21:11.380
of his newfound fascination,

21:11.600 --> 21:13.960
he began to be bombarded with shark mementos.

21:14.700 --> 21:16.180
What happened then, of course,

21:16.640 --> 21:17.840
was the older you get,

21:18.320 --> 21:20.380
I think the harder you are to shop for

21:20.380 --> 21:21.640
your friends and relatives.

21:21.940 --> 21:23.160
They don't know what to get you.

21:23.360 --> 21:24.780
They don't know what your tastes are.

21:24.880 --> 21:25.980
They don't know what books you've read

21:25.980 --> 21:27.860
or what albums you don't have.

21:29.940 --> 21:31.940
So somehow the shark story

21:31.940 --> 21:34.100
caught the fancy of the people around me

21:34.100 --> 21:36.060
and I started giving me shark paraphernalia.

21:36.160 --> 21:36.960
Before I knew it,

21:37.040 --> 21:39.200
I had more sharks than I knew what to do with.

21:39.960 --> 21:41.400
I'm glad it was sharks

21:41.400 --> 21:44.220
because Jaws notwithstanding,

21:44.240 --> 21:45.860
there never has been that much

21:45.860 --> 21:48.380
in the way of shark artifacts for sale.

21:48.540 --> 21:50.460
If it had been unicorns or dragons,

21:50.460 --> 21:52.020
say I would have been swamped

21:52.020 --> 21:52.760
completely and utterly

21:52.760 --> 21:54.360
and I could have knick-knack

21:54.360 --> 21:56.460
and gee-gaw garage sales.

21:57.340 --> 21:57.940
But instead,

21:58.160 --> 22:00.020
I've got some pretty neat shark stuff.

22:00.380 --> 22:02.460
Does Bryant really like sharks?

22:03.300 --> 22:04.360
I would say, though,

22:04.480 --> 22:06.700
that people ask me,

22:06.720 --> 22:08.480
do I really like sharks?

22:08.620 --> 22:09.180
And I have to admit,

22:09.260 --> 22:09.940
I don't like sharks.

22:10.040 --> 22:11.260
Nobody likes sharks,

22:11.860 --> 22:13.600
but I respect sharks.

22:14.340 --> 22:17.260
And sharks as an emblem,

22:17.480 --> 22:18.200
as a symbol,

22:19.140 --> 22:20.640
truly do fascinate me.

22:20.860 --> 22:22.340
And I expect there will be

22:22.340 --> 22:23.400
other shark stories.

22:23.720 --> 22:25.560
There may even be a shark novel.

22:25.740 --> 22:27.380
What militates against a shark novel,

22:27.540 --> 22:27.720
of course,

22:27.840 --> 22:30.160
quite aside from any of my own feelings

22:30.160 --> 22:31.220
about writing a novel,

22:31.380 --> 22:34.400
is I probably have to wait

22:34.400 --> 22:38.780
for the furore of Peter Benchley's Jaws

22:38.780 --> 22:40.560
to continue dying down.

