23:40.820 --> 23:42.000
Coming up next is

23:42.000 --> 23:43.520
the Science Fiction Radio Show,

23:43.680 --> 23:44.760
so stay with us.

24:00.660 --> 24:03.220
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show,

24:03.460 --> 24:06.040
a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

24:08.740 --> 24:10.440
And here are your hosts.

24:14.900 --> 24:16.180
This is David Carson.

24:16.200 --> 24:16.920
And Bill Vernon.

24:17.160 --> 24:18.420
In the fall of 1981,

24:18.860 --> 24:20.620
Edward Bryant's important short story collection,

24:20.800 --> 24:22.040
Particle Theory, was published.

24:22.320 --> 24:24.180
It contains memorable stories,

24:24.640 --> 24:25.580
"The Thermals of August",

24:25.860 --> 24:27.680
The Nebula Award-winning "giANTS",

24:27.980 --> 24:29.580
The often reprinted "Shark",

24:29.940 --> 24:31.120
"The Hibakusha Gallery",

24:31.340 --> 24:32.380
and the title story.

24:32.580 --> 24:34.180
The story "Particle Theory"

24:34.180 --> 24:35.780
is unique in Bryant's canon

24:35.780 --> 24:36.800
in that its background

24:36.800 --> 24:38.860
is heavily laden with hard science.

24:38.860 --> 24:41.000
Here he explains how any writer

24:41.000 --> 24:42.800
can get across hard science ideas

24:42.800 --> 24:44.680
if he uses the right resources.

24:45.600 --> 24:46.860
Particle theory came about

24:46.860 --> 24:48.600
because I read a newspaper article

24:48.600 --> 24:50.120
about pion beam therapy

24:51.240 --> 24:53.420
using a stream of solid particles,

24:53.560 --> 24:54.540
subnuclear particles,

24:54.580 --> 24:56.740
to attack cancerous tumors,

24:57.380 --> 24:59.200
which I have just found out

24:59.200 --> 25:00.160
is a line of research

25:00.160 --> 25:01.540
that has just been abandoned

25:01.540 --> 25:02.700
down at Los Alamos.

25:02.700 --> 25:03.880
I'm not sure why,

25:04.040 --> 25:05.220
whether it's funding cutbacks

25:05.220 --> 25:06.800
or whether they've simply found

25:06.800 --> 25:09.640
better means to attack the medical problem.

25:09.800 --> 25:10.400
But at any rate,

25:11.260 --> 25:12.460
what had intrigued me

25:12.460 --> 25:13.800
a number of years ago in the paper

25:13.800 --> 25:16.960
is now apparently scientifically dead.

25:18.160 --> 25:19.120
And yeah,

25:19.320 --> 25:21.440
this is more of a hard science story

25:21.440 --> 25:22.740
than I customarily write,

25:22.740 --> 25:26.100
but I think it exhibits

25:27.000 --> 25:29.020
a more general principle,

25:29.280 --> 25:30.800
which is that I

25:30.800 --> 25:32.360
or every other writer

25:32.360 --> 25:34.060
who may not be

25:34.060 --> 25:35.560
all that soundly based

25:35.560 --> 25:37.060
in science and technology

25:37.060 --> 25:38.580
by discipline

25:38.580 --> 25:40.160
or by vocation

25:40.160 --> 25:42.460
need simply only use

25:42.460 --> 25:44.060
the research tools

25:44.060 --> 25:45.300
that we all presumably learned

25:45.300 --> 25:46.080
in junior high

25:46.080 --> 25:47.500
to get across

25:47.500 --> 25:49.400
a hard science story

25:49.400 --> 25:52.900
without being overly didactic about it.

25:53.140 --> 25:54.920
What I discovered in this story

25:54.920 --> 25:56.200
was that the world

25:56.200 --> 25:57.140
is full of experts

25:57.140 --> 25:58.120
who were quite willing

25:58.120 --> 25:58.960
to share with me

25:58.960 --> 26:00.140
their specialized knowledge,

26:00.140 --> 26:00.800
whether it was

26:00.800 --> 26:02.180
particle beam physics

26:02.180 --> 26:03.360
or whether it was

26:03.360 --> 26:05.140
the landscape around Los Alamos

26:05.140 --> 26:08.540
and little details

26:08.540 --> 26:09.920
for verisimilitude,

26:09.920 --> 26:11.260
such as what airline

26:11.260 --> 26:13.100
do you fly into Los Alamos on

26:13.100 --> 26:14.340
and what sort of planes

26:14.340 --> 26:14.980
are you in

26:14.980 --> 26:16.600
and all of that kind of thing.

26:17.220 --> 26:18.460
Bryant comments here

26:18.460 --> 26:18.900
on the fact

26:18.900 --> 26:19.680
that he does not wish

26:19.680 --> 26:20.420
to be typecast

26:20.420 --> 26:20.880
as a writer

26:20.880 --> 26:22.420
of any particular type of story.

26:23.260 --> 26:23.740
True.

26:23.940 --> 26:24.340
Ordinarily,

26:24.340 --> 26:25.120
I don't use

26:25.120 --> 26:25.900
quite so much

26:25.900 --> 26:26.980
scientific content.

26:27.460 --> 26:27.980
All I can say

26:27.980 --> 26:29.360
is this was one of the stories

26:29.360 --> 26:30.560
in which that content

26:30.560 --> 26:31.620
seemed appropriate

26:32.840 --> 26:35.300
and it exhibits

26:36.100 --> 26:37.060
my own,

26:37.560 --> 26:38.280
in a sense,

26:38.400 --> 26:39.600
my own sense of frustration

26:40.160 --> 26:41.920
with being typecast.

26:42.620 --> 26:44.620
I write what I like to write

26:44.620 --> 26:45.660
and sometimes

26:45.660 --> 26:47.260
that may be a story

26:47.260 --> 26:48.260
which is full of

26:48.260 --> 26:49.640
medical research

26:49.640 --> 26:51.060
about prostate cancer

26:51.060 --> 26:54.040
and particle beam therapy

26:54.040 --> 26:55.800
for that cancer

26:55.800 --> 26:58.060
and cosmology,

26:58.880 --> 26:59.880
all that.

27:00.680 --> 27:01.280
And other times

27:01.280 --> 27:01.780
I will write

27:01.780 --> 27:02.940
science fiction stories

27:02.940 --> 27:04.520
in which there is not

27:04.520 --> 27:05.740
a speck

27:05.740 --> 27:07.160
of hard research

27:07.160 --> 27:08.280
or hard fact.

27:09.240 --> 27:09.920
Again,

27:09.960 --> 27:11.200
I suppose it illustrates

27:11.200 --> 27:11.640
the difference

27:11.640 --> 27:13.200
between facts and truths

27:13.200 --> 27:14.440
to be facile about it.

27:16.180 --> 27:17.840
But it also shows

27:17.840 --> 27:18.640
that good research

27:18.640 --> 27:19.820
can cover a multitude

27:19.820 --> 27:20.420
of sins.

27:20.760 --> 27:21.760
He maintains

27:21.760 --> 27:22.360
that even with

27:22.360 --> 27:23.660
the hard science elements,

27:23.960 --> 27:24.700
particle theory

27:24.700 --> 27:26.160
is still a people story.

27:26.640 --> 27:27.680
This story for me

27:27.680 --> 27:28.740
is still a people story

27:28.740 --> 27:29.640
first and foremost.

27:30.300 --> 27:31.260
It's, again,

27:31.420 --> 27:32.240
about relationships

27:32.240 --> 27:32.840
of people

27:32.840 --> 27:34.940
and the scientific content

27:35.620 --> 27:36.220
amplifies,

27:37.400 --> 27:38.000
illustrates,

27:38.160 --> 27:39.180
and I hope clarifies

27:39.180 --> 27:40.380
those relationships.

27:40.760 --> 27:41.900
But, by God,

27:42.060 --> 27:43.360
the people still come first

27:43.360 --> 27:44.520
and the science

27:44.520 --> 27:45.180
and technology

27:45.180 --> 27:45.800
come second.

27:51.820 --> 27:52.940
Bryant's first published

27:52.940 --> 27:53.880
short story collection,

27:54.100 --> 27:54.820
Among the Dead,

27:55.040 --> 27:56.180
came out in 1973.

27:56.560 --> 27:57.740
It contains a number

27:57.740 --> 27:58.520
of stories written

27:58.520 --> 27:59.480
early in his career.

27:59.760 --> 28:00.500
His novel,

28:00.660 --> 28:01.680
Phoenix Without Ashes,

28:01.800 --> 28:02.360
is in fact

28:02.360 --> 28:03.200
a novelization

28:03.200 --> 28:04.280
of Harlan Ellison's

28:04.280 --> 28:05.520
original pilot script

28:05.520 --> 28:06.540
for the ill-fated

28:06.540 --> 28:07.620
television series,

28:07.780 --> 28:08.700
The Star Lost,

28:08.700 --> 28:10.200
This work is a rarity.

28:10.400 --> 28:11.620
As a novelization,

28:11.860 --> 28:13.000
which came after the fact,

28:13.160 --> 28:13.860
it is actually

28:13.860 --> 28:15.020
a solid piece of work.

28:15.240 --> 28:16.380
The planned sequels

28:16.380 --> 28:17.740
have never materialized.

28:18.040 --> 28:18.600
Certainly,

28:18.720 --> 28:19.200
Edward Bryant

28:19.200 --> 28:20.200
has established himself

28:20.200 --> 28:21.320
as a top-flight writer

28:21.320 --> 28:22.540
who happens also

28:22.540 --> 28:23.640
to work under the label

28:23.640 --> 28:24.460
science fiction.

